\begin_layout Title
Status Consumption under uncertainty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The role of inequalities and status consumption is less understood.
 Instead of considering status consumption a wasteful consumption we use
 the importance of reference point that determine snob and bandwagon consumption.
 The model looks at how disposable income after having addressed basic needs
 may be spent in mechanisms that reward upside risk or mitigate downside
 risks to understand how a consumer's risk aversion might affect her future
 wealth - given exogenous mechanisms that both reward and mitigate risks.
 The basic question - how risk -aversion affects relative wealth.
 
\series bold
Can risk-averse consumer with lower budget gain by being more or less risk-avers
e than the other consumer?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With its various interpretations, conspicuous consumption - described as
 a higher than necessary consumption of quality or quantity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BritannicaConspCons2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - has often viewed as visible consumption in the literature.
 One could run into problems with this particular view of conspicuous consumptio
n in an environment of extreme wealth differences where long-term asset
 purchases - which also carry status - need to be distinguished from purportedly
 futile non-durable consumption that brings no utility in the regular sense.
 We consider these two types of consumption into a behavioural theory of
 risk to understand how the consumer's projected long-term future relative
 to a common reference could influence the competition for status - which
 we see as a probabilistic view of relative wealth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Arguing that the social and occupational structures could cause significant
 and stable differences in risk -aversion in an economy, we then look for
 the effects of differences in risk-aversion as well as the differences
 in income outlays on status consumption.
 In incorporating theory of decision of risk, we rule on the social-deference
 view of status suggested by Corneo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Coleman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where status consumption a means to offset an existing order of wealth
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankModel,corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The two kinds of status items are represented with a risky upsides investment
 and a protection against untoward circumstances in face of uncertainty
 presented by systemic risks in a macroeconomy.
 The consumer's optimise of expected wealth subject to their risk aversions
 is influenced by a common reference point as well.
\end_layout

