\begin_layout Standard
Veblen's ideas on consumption hvae revived interest in conspicuous consumption
 in the post-war era as the purchasing powers of consumers in the advanced
 economies have strengthened (see Galbraith
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GalbraithEssential"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Hirsch
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The expanding markets and far-reaching advertisement campaigns have suggested
 an ubiquity of status consumption (see the commentaries from Hirsch 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Goldman-Papson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GoldmanPapsonSignWars1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Baudrillard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BaudrillardSystem2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In the revival of Veblen's ideas, the popular discourse has presented a
 view conspicuous consumption as necessarily wasteful - whether as a behaviour
 exhibited by the ultra-rich or as a habit emulated by the poor.
 While Veblen does use pecuniary emulation and invidious comparison to explain
 the gilded age consumption, his observations on human behaviour pertaining
 to status consumption are general enough to view in light of the recent
 advances in behavioural sciences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of assuming that conspicuous consumption is limited to the rich
 and that the poor emulate unconditionally emulate them, we argue that the
 role of reference group is key to the idea of conspicuous consumption.
 Here, a conspicuous item either helps distance oneself from the others
 or provides a satisfaction of having achieved at least as much as others
 in the group - consequences that can be defined only with respect to a
 point of reference.
 This raises two important questions that we're explored in the current
 chapter.
 First, is if the reference point relevant for status consumption implied
 by the uncertainty in an economy.
 Second, would being further below from this reference point suggest a lower
 benefit from status consumption - thereby implying a limit to the gain
 from pecuniary emulation.
 The two questions could help us answer if the relative positioning with
 respect to a reference point determine when emulating the rich start to
 pay offs.
 We use probabilistic arguments to understand how optimising expected utility
 from relative wealth relative to a reference level could help answer these
 questions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relevance of reference points for status consumption has recently been
 noted in the empirical literature on status consumption.
 Chai et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - for example - find that competitions within peer-income groups are a
 better predictor for visible consumption in socio-economically apart groups
 in South Africa.
 It is likely that under extreme wealth differences, the poorest of a society
 would not compete with the richest sections of the society using conspicuous
 goods and indicate status only to their (poor) reference group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The broad understanding on status consumption is assisted with two classes
 of models in literature on status consumption that we have surveyed.
 The first is the set of social inference models - in particular those by
