 The rapid proliferation of industrial goods in the developing economies
 seems to have had an effect similar to that of visible items (see Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 , Ustuner-Holt
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 , Burke 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 on sub-Saharan Africa).
 The second set of models are based a social deference view of status (see
 Corneo
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 , Frank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankModel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

and Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and view status consumption as a means to alter the more stable wealth
