\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the later social ranking approach and use utility under risk to explain
 how status consumption could modify a ranking of wealth.
 Two key features of this projected utility are the reference level for
 the income and the level of risk-aversion exercised by the consumer.
 The role of reference point has been emphasised in the projection bias
 for future utility by Loewenstein et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LoewensteinProjectionBias2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The specific example used by Lowenstein
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LoewensteinProjectionBias2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is how a consumer buying a small house in a wealthy neighborhood tends
 often forget that her frame of reference quickly becomes larger houses
 owing to her new neighbours.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Karelis
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KarelisPoverty2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also suggests the importance of reference levels in the context of consumption
 under poverty.
 The notion of a reference point is key to snob or bandwagon interpretation
 of consumption as well.
 If a consumer wishes to catch up to a higher reference she is likely to
 choose a bandwagon type consumption whereas if she wants to move herself
 away from her current reference she might choose a snob type status item.
 It follows that the snob behaviour for a consumer with a low reference
 point could be bandwagon for another with a higher reference point.
 For example, a lawyer who sends her children for a degree in business may
 be pursuing a bandwagon consumption but a farmer who sends her children
 to in the same college the first time in generations may be exercising
 a snob behaviour.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-linear response to observed risk as varied degrees of risk-aversion
 has similarly been explored with many utility function forms in the behavioural
 economics literature.
 While risk-aversion parameters could be used with CRRA and CARA utility
 functions, the behavioural approaches have sought descriptive significance
 (see Prelec
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PrelecFunction1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Lowenstein
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LowensteinPrelecIntertemporalAnomalies1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) by using theories based on disappointment aversion (see Gul
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GulDisappointment1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 With a similar approach, Shefrin-Thaler 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ShefrinThaler1988"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 provide a mental accounting model - incorporating parameters such as willpower
 - to understand over-consumption and deviation from long-term goals.
 Unlike in the classical variants of the theory of consumer choice - where
 the consumer is subservient to her optimised plan for life-time savings
 and consumption - the representative consumer in a behavioural model can
 be subjected to overspending and acquiring habits she cannot afford (see
 Muellbauer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerRationalityMyopia1988."
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Fisher-Shell
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 to contrast with the classical treatment of habit formation and myopia
 in consumers).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A disappointment aversion approach that is cognisant of a reference point
 is suggested by the modern Prospect theory (PT) due to Kahneman-Tversky
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KahnemanTversykPT1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 While the applications of PT 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KahnemanTversykPT1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 treat the reference level as an empirical level set by the experimenter,
 a normative view relating reference points with future uncertainty of outcomes
 is suggested by Koszegi 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoszegiAnticipationPersonalEqlb2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The dynamic reference points in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Third Generation PT
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 uses a framework of anticipatory emotions to justify the selection of reference
 points (see Caplin-Leahy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CaplinLeahyAnticipatory2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Koszegi-Rabin
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoszegiRabin2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of status relevant in the the view of future outcomes depends
 both on reference level observed by the consumers and and risk -aversion
 differences among them.
 All consumers optimise a private view of status - which is shaped by a
 particular risk-aversion level.
 What status means to an individual differs from what it may mean for the
 group of individuals aggregated over a higher level.
 The high-status individual in one localised context is not necessarily
 of high-status in another but since the notions of power and net-asset-worth
 are shared across multiple contexts (societies, communities, nations etc.),
 we assume a common reference point for all consumers in the model.
 Formally, in groups 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{i}\}_{i\in[1,m]}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i\in[1,m]}$
\end_inset

 consumers in each group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 the consumers (
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{m}n_{i}$
\end_inset

in number) may all have a private view of status, but the notion of status
 associated with each group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

is determined by the long-term wealth the group has amassed.
 So while status at personal level might be subject to subjective uncertainties
 that are characteristics of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 the status at higher levels is indicated primarily by the material wealth
 associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 A more general formulation would consider multiple reference levels correspondi
ng to every group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 but with the current view of status, we view a single reference point as
 a long-term equilibrium observed by all consumers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Status consumption in the framework is a disproportionate amount of spending
 on items that serve no other purpose than boosting one's perceived status.
 The items for status consumption are purchases that enhance the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

private
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 view of one's status.
 The decision made for such purchases is determined by the projected utility
 that is subject to the consumer's risk-aversion and a common reference
 level.
 In other words, a consumer optimises a utility that is a function of the
 distance from the reference level -in monetary units.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The private view of the consumer's projected future which determines status
 consumption implies that the uncertainty perceived by the consumer may
 not be aligned with the risk in macroeconomic processes that determine
 her long-term income.
 The difference in the risk and uncertainty perceived by the consumer is
 modeled with a probability weighting function which representing the consumer's
 subjective non-linear response to the observed risk.
 The notions of subjective probability that this approach relies on have
 been around at least since Keynes
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KeynesProbability1921"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A formal treatment of subjective probability was offered by de Finetti
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vonPlato2012,deFinettiLaPrevision1937"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Empirical methods using consequence acts and Bayesian methods have been
 suggested in the late last century (see Savage
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Savage1972"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 - also see Schoemaker
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ShoemakerEU1982"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a discussion).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The risk aversion differences among the consumer are meant to indicate the
 occupational structures that result in the different attitudes to risk.
 So while a definite risk is entailed in a random process that all consumers
 are subjected to (regardless of their income), the consumer's uncertainty
 in projected utility is shaped by the individual characteristics that shape
 one's future uncertainty.
 In a canonical formulation of risk and perceived uncertainty, we use a
 Bernoulli random process 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E(W)=p$
\end_inset

) that affects all individuals in the economy.
 All macroeconomic changes in an economy such as the proliferation of new
 occupations, onslaught of calamities, rise of urbanisation, economic shocks
 and bubbles or political risks are meant to be represented by such a process.
 The gains and losses to an individual economy are represented as a repeated
 lottery that is played by all consumers as they observe the macroeconomic
 events simultaneously.
 The uncertain consumers decide to position themselves to benefit from gains
 in the economy or to seek protection from any losses that the economy is
 exposed to.
 Given a disposable income 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 - which we define as the consumer's expenditure after deducting the cost
 of her needs - a consumer can spend an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 towards the upside risk (probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) to be compensated 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi+P(\nu)$
\end_inset

 in a favourable enviroment and pay 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\xi)-\phi$
\end_inset

 in an unfavourable environment (with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p$
\end_inset

) .
 The disposable income as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 may vary for every consumer in the population.
 The lottery scheme presented to every consumer in the binary growth economy
 is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:binary-growth-economy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $x=\nu+\xi$
\end_inset

 ).
 In a more general setting, one could consider the returns from consumer's
 investments 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 to be stochastic as well - but in this canonical form we assume that the
 consumer may choose to spread her disposable income between competitive
 and cooperative investments that are rewarded through deterministic functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\xi)$
\end_inset

 respectively.
\end_layout

