 .
 In a more real-world settings, the returns from increased investments towards
 rewards are risky.
 In other words, a higher consumption of items that only reward upside risk
 often vary in the risks they offer.
 For example, a club membership offers low probability but high returns
 whereas investments in education may offers more guaranteed but lower returns.
 Representing both with a function 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\nu)$
\end_inset

 ignores the variation in risks associated with the two investments.
 Another limitation which can be easily addressed is absence of multiple
 reference points in our discussion.
 The goal of our discussion of reference points had been to endogenise the
 long-term reference point.
 Since the poor and the rich are likely to have separated consumption, an
 empirical application is more likely to mutliple reference points - which
 the consumer may switch between as her income changes.
 The conditions for the development of such reference points - i.e the feasbility
 and liquidity constraint - would remain the same.
 Our goal in this had been to illustrate the effect of occupational structures
 on risk-seeking and long-term reference points.
